  "footnotes": [
    "Gallic Empire (260–274): during the Crisis of the Third Century, Postumus established a breakaway Roman state comprising Gaul, Britannia, and Hispania; it maintained Roman institutions and was eventually reabsorbed by Emperor Aurelian",
    "Domain of Soissons (457–486): the last Roman-administered territory in Gaul, ruled by Syagrius; Clovis I's defeat of Syagrius at the Battle of Soissons (486) marked the end of Roman rule in Gaul",
    "Treaty of Verdun (843): the partition of the Carolingian Empire created West Francia, Middle Francia, and East Francia; West Francia became the nucleus of medieval France",
    "Burgundian State (1363–1477): the Valois Dukes of Burgundy built a powerful quasi-independent state stretching from Dijon to the Low Countries; Charles the Bold's death at Nancy (1477) ended the threat; France absorbed the Duchy while the Low Countries passed to the Habsburgs",
    "Albigensian Crusade (1209–1229): the crusade against the Cathar heresy in Languedoc destroyed Occitan independence and brought southern France under Capetian control",
    "French Revolution (1789): the collapse of the Ancien Régime began with the Estates-General; the Declaration of the Rights of Man established principles of popular sovereignty; the Storming of the Bastille (14 July) became the revolution's iconic moment",
    "Vichy France (1940–1944): after the Fall of France, Pétain's regime collaborated with Nazi Germany; de Gaulle's Free France movement maintained resistance and the claim to republican legitimacy"
  ]
}
